<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>
    
<section xml:id="sec-limits-concept">
<title>Introduction to Limits</title>
            
<p>
Consider the function <m>f(x) = 3x+5</m>. What happens as <m>x \to 1</m>?
We say that <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 1} (3x+5) = </m>.
</p>

<solution>
  <p>
    To find <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 1} (3x+5)</m>, we examine the function's behavior as <m>x</m> approaches <m>1</m> from both sides:
  </p>
  <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <term>From the left:</term> Let <m>x = 0.999999</m>.
          <me>f(0.999999) = 3(0.999999) + 5 = 2.999997 + 5 = 7.999997</me>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <term>From the right:</term> Let <m>x = 1.000001</m>.
          <me>f(1.000001) = 3(1.000001) + 5 = 3.000003 + 5 = 8.000003</me>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  <p>
    As <m>x</m> gets closer to <m>1</m> from both directions, <m>f(x)</m> approaches <m>8</m>. 
    Therefore, we say that <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 1} (3x+5) = 8</m>.
  </p>
  
  <figure xml:id="fig-limit-intro-graph">
    <caption>Graph of <m>f(x) = 3x+5</m> near <m>x=1</m></caption>
    <image xml:id="graph-3x5">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}
          \begin{axis}[
            axis lines = middle,
            xlabel = $x$,
            ylabel = {$f(x)$},
            xmin=0.5, xmax=1.5,
            ymin=6, ymax=10,
            xtick={1},
            ytick={8},
            grid=both
          ]
          \addplot [domain=0.5:1.5, blue, thick] {3*x+5};
          \addplot[only marks, mark=*, red] coordinates {(1,8)};
          \draw[dashed] (axis cs:1,0) -- (axis cs:1,8);
          \draw[dashed] (axis cs:0,8) -- (axis cs:1,8);
          \end{axis}
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
  </figure>
</solution>

<example xml:id="example-polynomial-limit">
<title>Limit of a Polynomial</title>
    <statement>
    <p>Find <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 2} (3x^2+2x-1)</m>. Justify your answer.</p>
    </statement>
 <solution>
    <p>
    Since <m>f(x) = 3x^2+2x-1</m> is a polynomial, it is continuous everywhere. 
    We can find the limit by direct substitution:
    <me>3(2)^2 + 2(2) - 1 = 3(4) + 4 - 1 = 12 + 4 - 1 = 15</me>.
    </p>
</solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-numerical-approach">
<title>Numerical Exploration of a Hole</title>
   <statement>
    <p>
    Consider the function: <m>\displaystyle f(x)=\frac{x^3-1}{x-1}</m>. 
    What happens to <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> gets closer to <m>1</m>?
    </p>
    <table xml:id="table-limit-values">
       <title>Numerical Values for <m>f(x)</m> near <m>x=1</m></title>
       <tabular halign="center">
           <row header ="yes" bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="major">
               <cell><m>x</m></cell>
               <cell><m>f(x)</m></cell>
               <cell><m>x</m></cell>
               <cell><m>f(x)</m></cell>
           </row>
           <row left="minor" right="minor" top="minor" bottom="minor">
               <cell>1.1</cell>
               <cell>3.31</cell>
               <cell>0.9</cell>
               <cell>2.71</cell>
           </row>
           <row left="minor" right="minor" top="minor" bottom="minor">
               <cell>1.01</cell>
               <cell>3.0301</cell>
               <cell>0.99</cell>
               <cell>2.9701</cell>
           </row>
           <row left="minor" right="minor" top="minor" bottom="minor">
               <cell>1.001</cell>
               <cell>3.003</cell>
               <cell>0.999</cell>
               <cell>2.997</cell>
           </row>
           <row left="minor" right="minor" top="minor" bottom="minor">
               <cell>1.0001</cell>
               <cell>3.0003</cell>
               <cell>0.9999</cell>
               <cell>2.9997</cell>
           </row>
       </tabular>
    </table>
    </statement>
<solution>
   <p>
       As <m>x</m> approaches 1 from both the left and the right, the values of <m>f(x)</m> 
       approach 3. Note that <m>f(1)</m> is undefined, but the limit exists.
   </p>
</solution>

</example>
<p>
Our algebraic result is the same as our numeric result. Our algebraic result is based on the following idea for what a limit should mean: 
<m>f(x)</m> gets closer and closer to <m>L</m> as <m>x</m> gets closer to <m>a</m>. 
The variable <m>x</m> never actually reaches <m>a</m>.
</p>

<exercise xml:id="ex-rational-limit-direct">
  <title>Direct Substitution in a Rational Function</title>
    <statement>
   <p>Calculate <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 2}\frac{x+3}{x+6}</m></p>
    </statement>
   <solution>
   <p>By direct substitution: <m>\frac{2+3}{2+6} = \frac{5}{8}</m>.</p>
    </solution>
</exercise>

 <exercise xml:id="ex-rational-limit-factor">
   <title>Limit by Factoring</title>
     <statement>
   <p>Calculate <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 1}\frac{x^2+x-2}{x^2-1}</m></p>
     </statement>
     <solution>
   <p>
    Factoring numerator and denominator: 
    <me>\lim_{x\to 1}\frac{(x+2)(x-1)}{(x+1)(x-1)} = \lim_{x\to 1}\frac{x+2}{x+1} = \frac{3}{2}</me>.
   </p>
     </solution>
</exercise>

<statement>
   <p>
       Consider the function <m>f</m> given by <m>f(x)=2x+3</m>. 
       Suppose we select input numbers <m>x</m> closer and closer to the number 4. 
       As input numbers approach 4 from either side, <m>2x+3</m> approaches 11.
   </p>
   <p>
       An arrow, <m>\rightarrow</m>, represents "approaches from either side." 
       The statement above can be written: <m>x \to 4, 2x+3 \to 11</m>.
       The number 11 is the limit, abbreviated as: <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \rightarrow 4}(2x+3)=11</m>.
   </p>
   <figure xml:id="fig-limit-graph">
       <caption>Graph of <m>f(x) = 2x+3</m> near <m>x=4</m></caption>
       <image xml:id="graph-2x3">
           <latex-image>
               \begin{tikzpicture}
  \begin{axis}[
      axis lines = middle,
      xlabel = $x$,
      ylabel = {$f(x)$},
      xmin=0, xmax=6,
      ymin=0, ymax=15,
      grid=both
  ]
  \addplot [domain=0:6, blue, thick] {2*x+3};
  \addplot[dashed] coordinates {(4,0) (4,11)};
  \addplot[dashed] coordinates {(0,11) (4,11)};
  \addplot[only marks, mark=*, red] coordinates {(4,11)};
  \node[label={180:{11}},circle,fill,inner sep=1pt] at (axis cs:0,11) {};
  \node[label={270:{4}},circle,fill,inner sep=1pt] at (axis cs:4,0) {};
  \end{axis}
               \end{tikzpicture}
           </latex-image>
       </image>
   </figure>
</statement>
            
<definition xml:id="def-limit">
<title>Limit of a Function</title>
  <statement>
   <p>
       A function <m>f</m> has the <term>limit</term> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> from either side, written 
       <me>\displaystyle\lim_{x \rightarrow a}f(x)=L</me>,
       if all values <m>f(x)</m> for <m>f</m> are close to <m>L</m> for values of <m>x</m> 
       that are arbitrarily close, but not equal, to <m>a</m>.
   </p>
    </statement>
</definition>

<p>
Limits and function values are not the same thing. Finding a limit is not the same 
as computing <m>f(x)</m>; a limit looks at where the function is going as it gets 
close to a point, not where it actually is at that point  <m>x=a</m> .
</p>

<example xml:id="example-dynamic-limit">
    <title>The Dynamic Limit Process</title>
                <statement>
   <p>Find <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 1} \frac{(x^2-1)}{(x-1)}</m></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
   <p>
       The value <m>f(1)</m> is undefined (<m>0/0</m>). However, factoring gives 
       <m>\frac{(x-1)(x+1)}{x-1} = x+1</m>. As <m>x \to 1</m>, <m>x+1 \to 2</m>.
   </p>
                </solution>
            </example>
<p>
The value <m> f(1) </m> of the function is not defined, since plugging in 
<m> x=1 </m> produces <m> 0/0,</m> whereas the values at points close to
 1, like <m> 1.01,.999,1.000045,</m> and so on, are perfectly well defined 
 and can be calculated. And if you calculate several of them you will notice 
 a definite trend: as you get closer to 1, the values converge to 2. 
</p>
<p>
    Suppose <m>f(x)</m> is given, and we would like to find the limit as <m> x\to a</m>. 
    We are interested in points in a neighborhood around <m> a,</m> points 
    close to <m> a,</m> points <m> x</m> such that <m> x-a</m> is a very small 
    (positive or negative) number. 
    If we call this small number <m> h</m>, 
    then this simply means 
</p>
<me> x - a = h , \text{ or equivalently } x = a + h </me>
<p>
    Note that even if <m> f(x) </m> is undefined at <m> x=a </m> (like the example above), 
    these nearby values can be calculated and the limit determined. 
</p>
 <p>
We can use the <m>h</m>-method to find limits by looking at a neighborhood <m>x = a + h</m> 
as <m>h \to 0</m>.
</p>

 <assemblage xml:id="h-method-formula">
   <p><me>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a} f(x)=\lim_{h\to 0} f(a+h)</me></p>
</assemblage>

<remark xml:id="remark-limit-steps">
    <title>The Three-Step Process for Limits</title>
    <p>
        The dynamic process of taking a limit is here broken down into three natural steps. 
        To find <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a} f(x)</m>:
    </p>
    <p>
        <ol marker="1">
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term>Evaluate</term> <m>f(a+h)</m>, a generic value at a nearby point.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term>Simplify</term>, collect terms, cancel common factors in the numerator and denominator, 
                    and otherwise reorganize this expression into a convenient form.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term>Limit</term>: Now we can let <m>h \to 0</m>. The remainders small (h) go to zero, 
                    and we are left with the residual limit:
                    <me>\lim_{x \to a} f(x)</me>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
</remark>
 <example xml:id="example-h-method-example">
    <title>Using the <m>h</m>-method</title>
    <statement>
   <p>Find <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 3} \frac{(x^2-3x)}{(2x-6)}</m></p>
    </statement>
 <solution>
  <p>
    <ol marker="1">
      <li>
        <p>
          Notice that <m>f(3)</m> is undefined, since both numerator and denominator zero out at <m>x=3</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Plug in <m>x=3+h</m> into the expression for <m>f(x)</m>:
          <me>f(3+h) = \frac{(3+h)^2-3(3+h)}{2(3+h)-6} = \frac{9+6h+h^2-9-3h}{6+2h-6}</me>
          with minimal expansion of terms.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Simplify and put into useful form:
          <me>f(3+h) = \frac{3h+ h^2}{2h} = \frac{3+h}{2}</me>
          after canceling <m>h</m> in the numerator and denominator.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Now let <m>h \to 0</m> without any problem:
          <me>\lim_{h \to 0} f(3+h) = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{3+h}{2} = \frac{3}{2}</me>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>
  <p>
    Therefore,
    <me>\lim_{x \to 3} \frac{x^2-3x}{2x-6} = \frac{3}{2}</me>
  </p>
</solution>

</example>

<exercise xml:id="ex-complex-rational">
  <title>Rational Function with Quadratic Factors</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>f(x)=\frac{2x^2-5x+2}{5x^2-7x-6}</m>, find <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to 2} f(x)</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <term>Method 1: Factoring</term>
    </p>
    <p>
      First, we factor the quadratic expressions in the numerator and denominator:
      <me>\frac{(2x-1)(x-2)}{(5x+3)(x-2)}</me>
      Since we are taking the limit as <m>x \to 2</m>, we assume <m>x \neq 2</m> and cancel the common factor:
      <me>\lim_{x \to 2} \frac{2x-1}{5x+3} = \frac{2(2)-1}{5(2)+3} = \frac{3}{13}</me>
    </p>

    <p>
      <term>Method 2: The <m>h</m>-method</term>
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>x = 2 + h</m>. As <m>x \to 2</m>, <m>h \to 0</m>. We substitute into the function:
      <md>
        <mrow>f(2+h) \amp = \frac{2(2+h)^2 - 5(2+h) + 2}{5(2+h)^2 - 7(2+h) - 6}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{2(4 + 4h + h^2) - 10 - 5h + 2}{5(4 + 4h + h^2) - 14 - 7h - 6}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{8 + 8h + 2h^2 - 10 - 5h + 2}{20 + 20h + 5h^2 - 14 - 7h - 6}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{3h + 2h^2}{13h + 5h^2} = \frac{h(3 + 2h)}{h(13 + 5h)}</mrow>
      </md>
      Canceling the <m>h</m> and letting <m>h \to 0</m>:
      <me>\lim_{h \to 0} \frac{3 + 2h}{13 + 5h} = \frac{3 + 0}{13 + 0} = \frac{3}{13}</me>
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

 </section>
    
